**Sec. 40001. Coast Guard Mission Readiness**
This section appropriates $24,593,500,000 to the Coast Guard for fiscal year 2025 to remain available until September 30, 2029, for procuring new assets and improving shore infrastructure. Specific allocations include $4,300,000,000 for Offshore Patrol Cutters, $4,300,000,000 for Polar Security Cutters, and $3,500,000,000 for Arctic Security Cutters to ensure presence in the Arctic and Antarctic. The funding also covers $1,142,500,000 for fixed-wing aircraft, $2,283,000,000 for rotary-wing aircraft, and $4,379,000,000 for shore facility construction, including $500,000,000 for the Coast Guard Yard. Additionally, $2,200,000,000 is designated for depot maintenance and $170,000,000 for maritime domain awareness improvements.

**Sec. 40002. Spectrum Auctions**
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) is authorized to grant licenses for at least 300 megahertz of spectrum, including 100 megahertz in the 3.98–4.2 gigahertz band within two years, while the Assistant Secretary of Commerce must identify 500 megahertz of federal frequencies for reallocation. The Assistant Secretary must identify 200 megahertz within two years and the remainder within four years, with the FCC required to auction at least 200 megahertz within four years and the rest within eight years. The President retains the authority to modify or withdraw frequencies up to 60 days before an auction if national security is threatened. To support these efforts, $50,000,000 is appropriated to the Department of Commerce for fiscal year 2025 to conduct spectrum analysis and publish biennial reports on federal spectrum value.

**Sec. 40003. Air Traffic Control Improvements**
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) receives $11,830,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to remain available until September 30, 2029, for modernizing telecommunications, replacing radar systems, and constructing a new Air Route Traffic Control Center (ARTCC). This funding mandates the divestment and integration of at least three existing ARTCCs into the new center and the closure or consolidation of at least ten existing ARTCCs under a realignment effort. Specific allocations include $4,750,000,000 for telecommunications, $3,000,000,000 for radar replacement, $1,900,000,000 for the new ARTCC, and $1,000,000,000 for terminal radar approach control (TRACON) consolidation. The FAA Administrator must submit quarterly reports to Congress detailing expenditures for these aviation safety improvements.

**Sec. 40004. Space Launch and Reentry Licensing and Permitting User Fees**
The Secretary of Transportation is authorized to impose fees on space launch and reentry licenses starting in 2026, calculated as the lesser of a per-pound rate (starting at $0.25 in 2026 and rising to $1.50 by 2033) or a flat fee (starting at $30,000 in 2026 and rising to $200,000 by 2033). These fees are deposited into a new fund, the Office of Commercial Space Transportation Launch and Reentry Licensing and Permitting Fund, with 70 percent available without further appropriation for the Office of Commercial Space Transportation. The fees are subject to annual increases based on the Consumer Price Index for all urban consumers starting in 2034. This mechanism establishes a self-sustaining revenue stream for the FAA's commercial space transportation regulatory activities.

**Sec. 40005. Mars Missions, Artemis Missions, and Moon to Mars Program**
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) receives $9,995,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to remain available until September 30, 2032, to fund Mars telecommunications, the Gateway lunar station, and Artemis IV and V missions. Specific allocations include $700,000,000 for a commercial Mars telecommunications orbiter, $2,600,000,000 for the Gateway program, and $4,100,000,000 for the Space Launch System for Artemis IV and V. The funding also covers $1,250,000,000 for International Space Station operations and $1,000,000,000 for infrastructure improvements at NASA centers, including $250,000,000 for Kennedy Space Center and $300,000,000 for Johnson Space Center. Funds must be obligated such that at least 50 percent is spent by September 30, 2028, and 100 percent by September 30, 2029.

**Sec. 40006. Corporate Average Fuel Economy Civil Penalties**
This section amends title 49, United States Code, to reduce the civil penalty for failing to meet Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards from $5 per vehicle to $0.00 for model years where the Secretary of Transportation has not yet issued a penalty notification. The amendment also reduces the penalty for exceeding the standard from $10 to $0.00, effectively eliminating these specific civil penalties for manufacturers. These changes take effect immediately upon enactment and apply to all model years where a penalty notification has not been previously provided. This action removes financial penalties for non-compliance with CAFE standards for the specified manufacturers and model years.

**Sec. 40007. Payments for Lease of Metropolitan Washington Airports**
The Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority must pay the U.S. Treasury an annual lease payment adjusted for the GNP Price Deflator, increasing from an inflation-adjusted $3,000,000 (1987 dollars) to $15,000,000 (2027 dollars) for the period starting in 2027. The Secretary of Transportation and the Airports Authority are required to renegotiate the lease payment level at least every 10 years to ensure the payment never falls below $15,000,000 in 2027 dollars. This amendment modifies section 49104(b) of title 49, United States Code, to reflect the new payment structure and renegotiation schedule. The change ensures a significant increase in revenue for the general fund starting in 2027.

**Sec. 40008. Rescission of Certain Amounts for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration**
This section permanently rescinds any unobligated balances of funds previously appropriated or made available by sections 40001, 40002, 40003, and 40004 of Public Law 117-169. The rescission applies specifically to amounts that were not spent or committed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) or other relevant entities under those prior laws. By cancelling these unspent funds, the government reduces the total budget authority available for NOAA's future operations related to these specific appropriations. This action effectively removes the remaining financial resources from the NOAA budget for the specified prior fiscal years.

**Sec. 40009. Reduction in Annual Transfers to Travel Promotion Fund**
The Travel Promotion Act of 2009 is amended to reduce the annual transfer to the Travel Promotion Fund from $100,000,000 to $20,000,000. This change directly lowers the federal funding allocated to the organization responsible for promoting the United States as a travel destination. The reduction takes effect immediately upon the enactment of this section, significantly decreasing the financial resources available for travel marketing and promotion efforts. This adjustment represents an 80 percent cut in the annual statutory transfer to the fund.

**Sec. 40010. Treatment of Unobligated Funds for Alternative Fuel and Low-Emission Aviation Technology**
This section permanently rescinds any unobligated balances of funds previously made available under section 40007(a) of title IV of Public Law 117-169, which supported alternative fuel and low-emission aviation technology. The rescission removes these unspent funds from the available budget, preventing their future use for the intended aviation technology programs. By cancelling these balances, the government reduces the overall funding commitment for alternative fuel initiatives in the aviation sector. This action ensures that only obligated funds remain active for the specified technology programs.

**Sec. 40011. Rescission of Amounts Appropriated to Public Wireless Supply Chain Innovation Fund**
This section permanently rescinds $850,000,000 of the unobligated balances made available under section 106(a) of the CHIPS Act of 2022 for the Public Wireless Supply Chain Innovation Fund. The rescission specifically targets funds that were not yet spent or committed to the public wireless supply chain innovation initiatives. By cancelling this amount, the government reduces the total funding available for developing secure and resilient public wireless supply chains. This action effectively removes $850,000,000 from the budget authority designated for the CHIPS Act's wireless supply chain components. [end of text]


